{{technical|date=September 2010}} In mathematics, a '''quantaloid''' is a [[Category (mathematics)|category]] [[Enriched category|enriched]] over the category '''Sup''' of ''[[Complete lattice#Morphisms of complete lattices|suplattices]]''.<ref>{{citation | last = Rosenthal | first = Kimmo I. | isbn = 0-582-29440-1 | mr = 1427263 | publisher = Longman, Harlow | series = Pitman Research Notes in Mathematics Series | title = The theory of quantaloids | volume = 348 | year = 1996}}. See in particular [https://books.google.com/books?id=O3bno8HpcFAC&pg=PA15 p.&nbsp;15].</ref> In other words for any objects ''a'', ''b'' the [[morphisms|morphism]] [[Category theory|object]] between them is not just a [[Set (mathematics)|set]] but a complete [[Lattice (order)|lattice]], in such a way that composition of morphisms preserves all joins:
<math>(\bigvee_i f_i) \circ (\bigvee_j g_j) = \bigvee_{i,j} (f_i \circ g_j) </math>
The endomorphism lattice <math>\mathrm{Hom}(X,X)</math> of any object <math>X</math> in a quantaloid is a [[quantale]], whence the name.
